<DOC><DOCNO> AP880725-0275 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1512EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f BC-AutoSales     07-25 0239</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Auto Sales,0247</SECOND><HEAD>Ford, Chrysler Daily Car Sales Rise</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: An AMer expected by 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Big Three automakers posted a 3.7 percentincrease on Monday in their daily domestic car sales in mid-July,as double-digit increases at Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp.offset a slight decline at General Motors Corp.   GM sold 106,791 cars in the July 11-20 period, up from 96,746 inthe mid-July period of 1987. But with nine days in the period thisyear and eight last year, GM's daily sales rate slowed by 1.9percent.   Ford sold 69,039 cars, up from 55,686 a year earlier and up 10.2percent on a daily basis, while Chrysler sold 29,956 cars, up from24,037 a year earlier and up 10.8 percent on a daily basis.   Overall, the Big Three sold 205,786 cars, up from 176,469 a yearearlier and 3.7 percent on a daily basis.   GM sold 53,434 domestically made light trucks, a 7.7 percentrise in daily sales and Chrysler sold 29,172, up 9.8 percent. Fordsold 45,426 light trucks, down 0.8 percent on a daily basis.   Honda Motor Co. sold 6,344 of its U.S.-made cars during theperiod for a 3.1 percent gain in daily sales. Toyota sold 1,745domestically produced autos, up from 874 in a period affected bytooling changes a year earlier.   Imported car and truck sales are reported at the end of eachmonth.</TEXT></DOC>